{{Orphan|date=December 2011}}

The '''complete glucose breakdown''' is a series of [[chemical reaction]]s representing transformation of [[glucose]] to [[adenosine triphosphate]] during the normal phases of aerobic [[cellular respiration]]. It is mostly done inside the [[mitochondria]] to release the maximum amount of [[energy]].<ref>[https://books.google.de/books?id=IegDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT85&lpg=PT85&dq=%22Complete+glucose+breakdown%22&source=bl&ots=baAPaQWShn&sig=r2pN9OCCkJZpbJLpjaUrm92louM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjslYCl-7XcAhXLEywKHQw7C2Y4ChDoATANegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22Complete%20glucose%20breakdown%22&f=false]</ref>

[[Pyruvate]] is made from glucose during the [[glycolysis]] and transformed to an [[acetyl group]] during transition reaction. The [[acetyl]] group is used in the [[Krebs cycle]] and the phase ends with the [[electron transport chain]].

