{{multiple image | footer = [[Kirk Gibson]] (at left, in 2011) and [[Dennis Eckersley]] (at right, in 2008), batter and pitcher of the [[walk-off home run]] in Game 1 of the [[1988 World Series]]. | image1 = Gibsonwin3.jpg | alt1 = A man in a baseball uniform | width1 = {{#expr: (200 * 300 / 415) round 0}} | image2 = Dennis Eckersley 2008 (crop).jpg | alt2 = A man in a jacket without a tie | width2 = {{#expr: (200 * 1550 / 2300) round 0}} |}} '''[[Kirk Gibson]]'s 1988 World Series home run''' occurred in Game 1 of the [[1988 World Series]], on October 15, {{mlby|1988}}, at [[Dodger Stadium]] in [[Los Angeles]]. Gibson, [[pinch hitter|pinch hitting]] for the [[1988 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the bottom of the ninth [[inning (baseball)|inning]], with injuries to both legs, hit a two-run [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] [[home run]] off the [[1988 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]]' [[Dennis Eckersley]] that won Game 1 for the Dodgers by a score of 5&ndash;4.
After winning the [[National League]] [[National League West|West]] division, the Dodgers were considered the [[underdog (competition)|underdogs]] throughout the 1988 postseason, first to the [[1988 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] in the [[1988 National League Championship Series|NLCS]], then to the A's in the World Series. Gibson, who was not expected to play due to injuries in both legs sustained during the NLCS, was surprisingly inserted as a [[pinch hitter]] with the Dodgers trailing 4&ndash;3 with two [[out (baseball)|out]]s and the tying run at first base in the bottom of the ninth inning. Gibson's home run&mdash;his only [[plate appearance]] of the series&mdash;helped the Dodgers defeat the A's, 4 games to 1, securing their sixth [[World Series]] title.
The play has since become legendary in the baseball world, and is regarded as one of the greatest home runs of all time.<ref name="Time.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1650858_1650857_1650844,00.html|title=Historic Home Runs: Kirk Gibson's World Series Walk-off Home Run|publisher=Time.com|accessdate=2009-03-30 | date=2007-08-08}}</ref> It was voted the "greatest moment in L.A. sports history" in a 1995 poll.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/oct/15/sports/sp-gibson15|title=Reliving the moment of home run by Dodgers' Kirk Gibson, 20 years later|last=Mitchell|first=Houston|date=2008-10-15|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref> Many of the images associated with the home run, particularly Gibson pumping his fist while circling the bases, are often shown in classic highlight reels, usually accompanied by [[Vin Scully]] or [[Jack Buck]]'s call. Though not related to his World Series home run, Gibson would be named the 1988 NL [[Most Valuable Player|MVP]]. He was named to two [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] teams (1985 in the AL, and 1988 in the NL), but declined both invitations.
==Background==
===Regular season=== [[File:Orel Hershiser 1993.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Orel Hershiser]] would be named the 1988 [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP]].]] The Dodgers signed [[outfielder]] Kirk Gibson as a [[free agent]] during the 1988 offseason. Gibson, who played the previous nine seasons with the [[Detroit Tigers]] (winning a World Series title with them in [[1984 World Series|1984]]), quickly became the Dodgers' de facto leader both on the field and off. On the field, Gibson led the team with 25 home runs, a .290 [[batting average]] and 31 stolen bases.
The [[1987 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]], who had only finished 4th in the [[National League West]] in [[1987 Major League Baseball season|1987]] with a 73–89 ({{winpct|73|89}}) record (17 games behind the division winning [[1987 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]]), led the NL West division standings from late May until the end of the season, easily winning the division title with a record of 94&ndash;67 ({{winpct|94|67}}), seven games ahead of the second-place [[1988 Cincinnati Reds season|Cincinnati Reds]].
One reason why the Dodgers were considered underdogs throughout the postseason was that they did not finish the regular season ranked in the top five of any major offensive statistical category. However, they were strengthened by an excellent [[starting pitcher|starting rotation]] led by ace [[Orel Hershiser]] and backed up by [[Tim Belcher]], [[John Tudor (baseball)|John Tudor]] and [[Tim Leary (baseball)|Tim Leary]]. They also had an outstanding [[bullpen]] that included [[Jay Howell]], [[Jesse Orosco]] and [[Alejandro Peña]].
===Postseason=== Their opponent in the [[1988 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]] was the [[1988 New York Mets season|New York Mets]], who had compiled a more impressive 100&ndash;60 ({{winpct|100|60}}) regular season record, and had won 10 of their 11 regular-season meetings with the Dodgers. The NLCS was a surprisingly close contest given the outcomes of the two teams' regular season meetings. Gibson's heroics in the series included an improbable catch on wet grass in Game 3 and decisive home runs in Games 4 and 5. The series went to a deciding Game 7, which the Dodgers won in stunning fashion on the back of Hershiser's 5 hit shutout to earn their first [[World Series]] trip since [[1981 World Series|1981]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAN/LAN198810120.shtml 1988 NLCS Game 7 Box Score]</ref> Gibson injured his left hamstring while stealing second base in Game 5 and his right knee while sliding into second base in Game 7.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Suchon|first1=Josh|title=Miracle Men: Hershiser, Gibson, and the Improbable 1988 Dodgers|date=2013|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=9781600788062|page=216-217|chapter=NLCS}}</ref><ref name="Chass1989">{{cite news|last1=Chass|first1=Murray|title=Baseball; Gibson Still Bothered by Knee|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/24/sports/baseball-gibson-still-bothered-by-knee.html|accessdate=14 August 2017|work=The New York Times|date=24 February 1989}}</ref>
After defeating the Mets, the Dodgers faced the [[1988 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] in the [[1988 World Series|World Series]]. Oakland had compiled a 104&ndash;58 ({{winpct|104|58}}) regular season record (the best in the Majors), and boasted a powerful lineup led by sluggers [[Jose Canseco]] and [[Mark McGwire]], and complemented by the likes of [[Dave Henderson]], [[Dave Parker]] and [[Don Baylor]]. The A's, who also boasted 20 game winner [[Dave Stewart (baseball)|Dave Stewart]] (himself a former Dodger from 1978-1982) and [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Dennis Eckersley]] who had saved 45 games during the regular season, had easily accounted for [[Boston Red Sox|Boston]] in the [[1988 American League Championship Series|ALCS]], sweeping the Red Sox 4–0.
==The setup==
===World Series Game 1=== Gibson injured both legs during the NLCS, and therefore did not start Game 1. Los Angeles took an early lead on an improbable two-run home run by [[Mickey Hatcher]] in the first inning. The next inning, however, Canseco hit a [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] to give Oakland a two-run lead. Oakland's lead was cut to one run when [[Mike Scioscia]] hit an [[RBI]] [[single (baseball)|single]] in the sixth inning that scored [[Mike Marshall (outfielder)|Mike Marshall]].
[[File:Mike Davis 1986.JPG|thumb|right|upright|[[Mike Davis (baseball)|Mike Davis]], shown here with Oakland, drew a walk ahead of Gibson's at bat, and was on base as the Dodgers' potential tying run.]] Unknown to the fans and the media at the time, Gibson was watching the game on television while undergoing physical therapy in the Dodgers' clubhouse.<ref name="USAToday">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/playoffs/2008-10-06-gibson-88homer_N.htm|title=Kirk Gibson's 1988 home run still a World Series highlight|last=Lopresti|first=Mike|date=2008-10-08|work=USA Today|accessdate=2009-03-25}}</ref> At some point during the game, television cameras scanned the Dodgers [[dugout (baseball)|dugout]] and commentator [[Vin Scully]], working for [[NBC]] for the 1988 postseason, observed that Gibson was "nowhere to be found".<ref name="USAToday" /> This spurred Gibson to tell Dodgers [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Tommy Lasorda]] that he was available to [[pinch hitter|pinch hit]].<ref name="USAToday" /> Gibson immediately returned to the [[batting cage]] in the clubhouse to take practice swings.<ref name="USAToday" />
With a one-run lead, Oakland [[closing pitcher|closer]] [[Dennis Eckersley]], who led the AL with 45 saves during the regular season, was brought in to close out the game and seal the win for starter [[Dave Stewart (baseball)|Dave Stewart]]. Eckersley quickly got Scioscia to pop out to [[shortstop]] and struck out [[Jeff Hamilton (baseball)|Jeff Hamilton]]. Left-handed [[pinch hitter]] [[Mike Davis (baseball)|Mike Davis]] followed; if he got on base the next batter due was the pitcher's spot, which would certainly be filled with a pinch hitter. Not wanting the A's to realize that Gibson was available, Lasorda sent [[Dave Anderson (infielder)|Dave Anderson]] to the on-deck circle during Davis' plate appearance.<ref name="USAToday" /> According to Lasorda, A's catcher [[Ron Hassey]] got Eckersley's attention and pointed at Anderson on-deck.<ref name="LATimes">{{cite news|last1=Lasorda|first1=Tom|title=Gibson's homer in Lasorda's words|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/oct/16/sports/sp-lasorda16|accessdate=14 August 2017|work=Los Angeles Times|date=16 October 2008}}</ref> The popular story is that Eckersley pitched around Davis because the A's thought that the light-hitting Anderson was the next batter. Hassey vehemently denied that the A's pitched carefully to Davis because Anderson was on deck: "Why would we pitch around Davis when we have two outs? You don't pitch around a guy with two outs to face another hitter. That would never make sense. You have your closer out there. That's just not true. That's a good story. As far as I know, Gibson is on the roster. Is he not? You're not going to waste a guy that can't play. He's active." Eckersley decided to pitch around Davis because he had seen him hit 20 home runs for the A's before the All-Star break the previous year. Instead of risking making a mistake that Davis could hit for a game-tying home run, Eckersley pitched carefully and did in fact [[base on balls|walk]] him.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Suchon|first1=Josh|title=Miracle Men : Hershiser, Gibson, and the Improbable 1988 Dodgers|date=2013|publisher=Triumph Books|location=Chicago|isbn=9781600788062|page=245-246|chapter=World Series Game 1}}</ref>
==The play== [[File:Dodger Stadium.jpg|thumb|[[Dodger Stadium]], where the home run was hit.]]
Instead of sending Anderson to the plate, Lasorda inserted Gibson as his pinch hitter. Gibson hobbled up to the plate with Scully commenting, ''"And look who's coming up!"'' Gibson quickly fouled off two pitches, getting behind in the [[Count (baseball)|count]], 0&ndash;2. He then swung clumsily and dribbled the ensuing pitch foul down the first base line, which seemed to confirm his inability to swing with any authority. Gibson took an outside pitch, called a ball by home plate umpire [[Doug Harvey (umpire)|Doug Harvey]], fouled off a pitch, and then took another outside pitch to work to a 2&ndash;2 count.
On the seventh pitch of the [[at bat]]—another ball, making it a [[full count]]—Davis [[stolen base|stole]] second. Dodger manager Tommy Lasorda later recounted it was pre-planned that if the count got to two strikes on Gibson, they would have Davis steal second, figuring that A's manager [[Tony La Russa]] wouldn't elect to [[Intentional walk|intentionally walk]] Gibson if there were already two strikes against him. Once Davis was at second, Lasorda was just hoping Gibson could muscle a pitch to the outfield for a game-tying single.<ref name="LATimes" />
Gibson would later recount that prior to the Series, Dodger scout [[Mel Didier]] had provided a report on Eckersley which claimed that with a 3&ndash;2 count against a [[left-handed]] hitter, one could be absolutely certain that Eckersley would throw a [[List of baseball jargon (B)#backdoor breaking ball|backdoor]] [[slider]].<ref name="USAToday"/> Gibson said that when the count reached 3&ndash;2, he stepped out of the batter's box and, in his mind, could hear Didier's voice, with its distinctive [[Southern American English#Phonology|Southern drawl]], reiterating that same piece of advice.<ref name="USAToday"/> With that thought in mind, Gibson stepped back into the batter's box; and thus when Eckersley did in fact throw a backdoor slider, it was exactly the pitch Gibson was expecting.
Swinging almost entirely with his upper body, Gibson then hit the pitch over the right-field fence. He limped around the bases and pumped his fist as his teammates stormed the field. The Dodgers won the game, 5&ndash;4.
Gibson did not have another plate appearance in the World Series. The Dodgers went on to defeat the A's in the World Series, 4–1.
==The calls==
===[[Don Drysdale]]=== {{quote|Well, the crowd on its feet and if there was ever a preface, to "[[Casey at the Bat]]," it would have to be the ninth inning. Two out. The tying run aboard, the winning run at the plate, and Kirk Gibson, standing at the plate.
Gibson, a deep sigh ... re-gripping the bat ... shoulders just shrugged ... now goes to the top of the helmet, as he always does ... steps in with that left foot. Eckersley, working out of the stretch ... here's the three-two pitch ... and a drive hit to right field (voice changes to high pitch) WAY BACK! THIS BALL ... IS GONE! (After delay) This crowd will not stop! They can't believe the ending! And this time, Mighty Casey did NOT strike out!}}
===Vin Scully=== [[File:Scully GM.JPG|thumb|right|[[Major League Baseball on NBC|NBC]] television announcer [[Vin Scully]]]] {{quote|All year long, they looked to him to light the fire, [Scully began]}} {{quote|and all year long, he answered the demands, until he was physically unable to start tonight&mdash;with two bad legs: The bad left hamstring, and the swollen right knee. And, with two out, you talk about a roll of the dice... this is it.}}
Scully, calling the play-by-play for the [[Major League Baseball on NBC|NBC]]-TV (as previously mentioned) broadcast with [[color commentator]] [[Joe Garagiola, Sr.|Joe Garagiola]], made repeated references to Gibson's legs, noting at one point that the batter was {{quote|shaking his left leg, making it quiver, like a horse trying to get rid of a troublesome fly.}}
Gibson worked the count to 3&ndash;2 as Mike Davis stole second base; the camera turned at that point to [[Steve Sax]] getting ready for his turn at the plate, and Scully reminded the viewers that {{quote|Sax waiting on deck but the game right now is at the plate.}}
{{quote|High fly ball into right field, she i-i-i-is... GONE!!!}}
Scully said nothing for over a minute, allowing the pictures to tell the story. Finally, he said, {{quote|In a year that has been so improbable... the ''impossible'' has happened!}}
Returning to the subject of Gibson's banged-up legs during a replay, Scully joked, {{quote|And, now, the only question was, could he make it around the base paths unassisted?!}}
{{quote|You know, I said it once before, a few days ago, that Kirk Gibson was not the Most Valuable Player; that the Most Valuable Player for the Dodgers was [[Tinkerbell]]. But, tonight, I think Tinkerbell backed off for Kirk Gibson. And, look at Eckersley&mdash;shocked to his toes!}}
{{quote|They are going wild at Dodger Stadium&mdash;no one wants to leave!}}
As NBC showed a replay of Gibson rounding second base in his home run trot, Scully then made a point to note Eckersley's pitching performance throughout the 1988 season, to put things in perspective.
{{quote|Dennis Eckersley allowed five home runs all year. And we'll be back.}}
===Jack Buck=== [[File:Jackbuck.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Major League Baseball on CBS Radio|CBS Radio]] announcer [[Jack Buck]]]] [[Major League Baseball on CBS Radio|CBS]] handled the national radio broadcast of the 1988 World Series, with [[Jack Buck]] providing play-by-play and [[Bill White (first baseman)|Bill White]] as the analyst. This was Buck's call. It begins here with Buck speculating on what might happen if Gibson manages to reach base:
{{quote|... then you would run for Gibson and have Sax batting. But, we have a big 3&ndash;2 pitch coming here from Eckersley. Gibson ''swings'', and a fly ball to deep right field! ''This is gonna be a home run!!!'' Unbelievable! A home run for Gibson! And the Dodgers have won the game, five to four; I don't believe what I just saw!!!}}
The last sentence is often remembered and quoted by fans. Buck followed it with, {{quote|I don't ''believe'' what I just saw! Is this really happening, Bill?}}
Buck concluded his comments on Gibson's amazing feat with this thought: {{quote|One of the most remarkable finishes to any World Series Game...a one-handed home run by Kirk Gibson! And the Dodgers have won it...five to four; and I'm stunned, Bill. I have seen a lot of dramatic finishes in a lot of sports, but this one might top almost every other one.}}
==Aftermath==
Much was made about Eckersley's decision to throw an offspeed pitch to Gibson, with Joe Garagiola repeatedly noting that Gibson clearly couldn't catch up to a fastball. To his credit, Eckersley fielded every reporters' question after the game, mostly blaming himself. Years later, he recalled, "Somebody said that the Dodgers knew I threw a backdoor slider on 3&ndash;2. I don’t know if that’s true or not. I didn’t get to 3&ndash;2 that often, but if that’s what the guy told him [Gibson], if that’s what he had on his mind, good for him. Either way, it was a terrible slider."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/strike-zone/2013/10/15/kirk-gibson-dennis-eckersley-dodgers-athletics-1988-world-series-home-run-oral-history# |title='That was a cool feeling': An oral history of Kirk Gibson's iconic 1988 home run |publisher=''Sports Illustrated'' |date=October 15, 2013 |accessdate=April 5, 2017}}</ref>
The home run was included as a finalist in a Major League Baseball contest to determine the sport's "Greatest Moment of All-Time." For years after the fact, it was regularly used in ''[[This Week in Baseball]]'s'' closing montage sequence. An edited audio of Scully's 1988 call has been used in {{By|2005}} post-season action, in a TV ad featuring a recreational softball game, with a portly player essentially re-enacting that entire moment as he hits the softball over the right field fence to win the game. It was in competition on [[ESPN]]'s ''[[SportsCenter]]'' for the Greatest Sports Highlight of All-Time.
By the time Gibson returned to his locker for postgame interviews, Dodger bullpen coach Mark Cresse had taped the name of Roy Hobbs over Gibson's nameplate, in reference to Gibson's heroics mirroring those of the film slugger that [[Robert Redford]] had played in ''[[The Natural (film)|The Natural]]''. Like Hobbs in the film's climactic scene, Gibson had represented the winning run when he came to the plate, had been down to his (and the team's) final strike and had homered to right field to win the game. NBC's pregame video for Game 2 narrated by [[Bob Costas]] included both the home run and its film counterpart.<ref>[https://vimeo.com/75729831 1988 World Series Game 1 Recap (Game 2 Pregame): Kirk Gibson in ''The Natural''] Vimeo (originally broadcast by NBC)</ref>
The fate of the ball itself is unknown. According to Gibson, a woman sent him a picture of the bruise on her leg where the ball hit her, although no one has yet come forward with the ball.<ref name="Time.com"/> In fiction, a court struggle over the ownership of the ball was the primary plot of the June 29, 2011, episode of [[Turner Network Television|TNT]] legal drama ''[[Franklin & Bash]]''.
Near the end of the Major League Baseball season in the fall of 2011, [[Chevrolet]] began airing commercials for their Diamond & Dream's Program, a giveaway designed to help the youth in their communities around the country. Prizes included a makeover for their baseball field. The commercials showed selected little league baseball players acting out some of baseball's greatest moments in history. One of them being Kirk Gibson's famous home run from the 1988 World Championship run of the Los Angeles Dodgers. The young boy acting out this moment could be seen running the bases, doing the same fist pump motion that Gibson was seen doing during his famous run around the bases.
The structure, tone, and overall style of [[Ernest Thayer]]'s famous poem "[[Casey at the Bat|Casey at the Bat: A Ballad of the Republic Sung in the Year 1888]]"—first published in 1888 and "the single most famous baseball poem ever written" according to the [[Baseball Almanac]]<ref name=Almanac>{{cite web|title=Casey at the Bat by Ernest Thayer|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/poetry/po_case.shtml|publisher=Baseball Almanac|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>—was [[literary adaptation|adapted]] by Michael J. Farrand in 2000 to create "The Man Who Gave All the Dreamers in Baseball Land Bigger Dreams to Dream" about the Gibson home run, but this time reversing the infamous outcome. This adaptation appears at the Baseball Almanac. Farrand's choice of poetic model was prompted by the observation of [[Mike Scioscia]], then the Dodger catcher: "It was 'Casey at the Bat,' except this time Casey hits a home run."<ref>"[http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jul/24/sports/sp-hall24 More Than That One Pitch: Eckersley, who gave up Gibson's '88 homer, makes Hall as the dominant closer of his era.]" BASEBALL HALL OF FAME Induction ceremony, Sunday, 10:30 a.m., ESPN Classic; July 24, 2004 by Bill Shaikin for Los Angeles Times</ref> For his part, Gibson said: "It really was not that bad a pitch, and I put an ugly swing on it." In the words of the poem: :Eck winds, curls, and releases the ball, all without a hitch :Gibby's swing is something ugly, an army-wristy stab :His wrenching follow-through suggests he won't survive the jab.
In Game 4 of the [[2018 World Series]], 30 years after that 1988 World Series walk-off home run, Eckersley and Gibson reunited for the ceremonial first pitch at [[Dodgers Stadium]]; Gibson had a bat ready before catching Eckersley's pitch.<ref>https://sports.yahoo.com/kirk-gibson-dennis-eckersley-reunite-30-years-later-world-series-first-pitch-002825561.html</ref>
