'''NUI Galway RFC''' is the rugby team of [[NUI Galway]]. Their colours are maroon and white.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://domestic.connachtrugby.ie/content/view/68/9/ |title=UCG |publisher=Domestic.connachtrugby.ie |date=2006-09-27 |accessdate=2010-01-21}}</ref> The rugby club in NUIG was founded in 1874, which makes it the oldest club in Connacht.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} They played in the [[Bateman Cup]] competition many times and won their first Connacht Senior Cup in 1897. They have held this trophy aloft 34 times in all, more than any other club in the Connacht,{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} and they have won the senior league 16 times. They won the Dudley Cup for the first time in 1905. They have had many successes down through the years, but a real highlight was the 1962/63 season when they swept the boards — they won the Connacht Minor League and Minor Cup, the Connacht Junior League and Junior Cup, the Connacht Senior League and Senior Cup, the OLBC Sevens and the Blake Sevens.<ref>{{cite news|first=Tom|last=Kenny|url=http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/60129/ucg-rugby-club|title=UCG Rugby Club|work=[[Galway Advertiser]]|date=11 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808051832/http://www.advertiser.ie/galway/article/60129/ucg-rugby-club|archivedate=8 August 2014}}</ref>
Many of their players have played for Irish universities international teams, and 10 have been capped for Ireland, several while playing for UCG. One of those, Ciaran Fitzgerald, captained the British and Irish Lions.
Currently NUIG do not compete in the [[All-Ireland League (rugby union)|All-Ireland League]], but they field two teams at Junior level (J1B & J2) and their under-20 team plays in the Conroy Cup against UCC, UCD, QUB, and TCD, along with competing in the Under-20 JP Fanagan Leinster League. They have also set up a Rugby Youth Academy in an attempt to help strengthen the club.
The women's team was set up in the 2002-2003 season. Their first official game was in 2004 versus Sligo I.T. In the 2008/2009 season NUIG women won the Connacht League. In the 2012/2013 season NUIG contested the [[Colleges & Universities Sports Association of Ireland]] Div 1 College League Final against UL. In 2013/2014 and again in 2014/2015 NUIG won the [[Irish Universities Rugby Union]] Kay Bowen Intervarsity Cup.
==Notable players== * [[Steve Cunningham (IRFU)|Steve Cunningham]] * [[Seamus Dennison]] — played for [[Munster rugby|Munster]] in [[History of rugby union matches between Munster and New Zealand#1978|their historic 1978 defeat]] of the [[New Zealand national rugby union team|All Blacks]] at [[Thomond Park]], executing a much heralded tackle against his opponents<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/rugby/where-are-they-now-seamus-dennison-abbeyfeale-1947-25950552.html|title=Where are they now? Seamus Dennison (Abbeyfeale 1947)|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]|date=7 December 2005|accessdate=7 December 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/rugby/where-are-they-now-28821560.html|title=WHERE ARE THEY NOW?|work=Sunday Independent|date=21 October 2012|accessdate=21 October 2012|quote=University in Galway was his next stop. He lined out for Connacht while there and also made the combined Universities team.}}</ref> * [[Ciaran Fitzgerald]] — captained the [[British and Irish Lions|British and Irish Lion]]s and [[Connacht Rugby|Connacht]] and won a [[Triple Crown (Rugby Union)|Triple Crown]] while captaining [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]] * [[Neville Furlong]] — scored the last try worth four points by an Irish player before a change in the game's rules * [[Eamonn McGuire]] — played for [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/argus/news/eamonn-was-a-great-sportsman-29601621.html|title=Eamonn was a great sportsman|work=[[The Argus (Dundalk)|The Argus]]|date=18 September 2013|accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/obituaries/a-rugby-great-who-played-for-connacht-and-country-1.1613402|title=A rugby great who played for Connacht and country: Eamonn McGuire - Born: June 28th, 1939; Died: September 14th, 2013|work=The Irish Times|date=30 November 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181125030204/https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/people/obituaries/a-rugby-great-who-played-for-connacht-and-country-1.1613402|archivedate=25 November 2018|quote=He studied engineering at University College Galway, where he won several Connacht Senior League and Cup titles. His sprinter’s speed helped him to become a try scorer and after making a big impact playing for UCG he was chosen on the Combined Universities team, playing on the team that famously beat the touring South Africans.}}</ref> * [[Mick Molloy (rugby)|Mick Molloy]] — earned 27 caps for Ireland between 1966 and 1973 * [[Dickie Roche]] — played for [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], including when at university<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.connachtrugby.ie/dick-roche-rip/|title=Dick Roche RIP|work=[[Connacht Rugby]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117003249/https://www.connachtrugby.ie/dick-roche-rip/|archivedate=17 November 2018|quote=From Woodford in Galway, Roche was one of the first Connacht-born players to represent Ireland in the 1950s and the first to do so while playing with a Connacht club. He attended Garbally College in Ballinasloe and represented both UCG and Galwegians RFC.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tuamherald.ie/sport/roundup/articles/2014/03/28/4026467-the-galway-man-denied-a-very-special-place-in-international-rugby-history-by-a-disallowed-score-|title=The Galway man denied a very special place in international rugby history by a disallowed score|work=[[Tuam Herald]]|date=25 April 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180201192826/http://www.tuamherald.ie/sport/roundup/articles/2014/03/28/4026467-the-galway-man-denied-a-very-special-place-in-international-rugby-history-by-a-disallowed-score-|archivedate=1 February 2018|quote=Despite that, the West got international recognition as far back as Henry J. Anderson in 1903, followed in the next 60 years by the likes of Sligo-born Aengus McMorrow in 1951; the dynamic Dickie Roche from Woodfo