{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2012}} [[File:Bjorkman and Woodbridge winners Wimbledon 2004.jpg|thumb|right|2002 – 2004 Wimbledon doubles champion, [[Todd Woodbridge]] from Australia and [[Jonas Björkman]] from Sweden]] The '''Wimbledon effect''' (Japanese: ウィンブルドン現象, [[rōmaji]]: ''Uinburudon Genshō'', literally "Wimbledon Phenomenon") is a chiefly British and Japanese analogy (which possibly originated in Japan<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/globalisation/story/0,7369,1242513,00.html "Leader: Foreign ownership – Importing success"], 19 June 2004, ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>Amory, Edward Heathcoat : [http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3724/is_199806/ai_n8795065 "A fearful symmetry"], 6 June 1998, ''[[The Spectator]]''</ref>) which compares the tennis fame of the [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon Championships]], held at the [[All England Lawn Tennis and Croquet Club]] in [[Wimbledon, London]], with the economic success of the United Kingdom's [[financial services]] industries – especially those clustered in the [[City of London]].
The point of the analogy is that a national and international institution (the All England Club) can be highly successful despite the lack of strong native competition, as in modern tennis Britain has produced very few Wimbledon champions, with only [[Ann Haydon Jones]], [[Virginia Wade]] (both women's singles), [[Jonathan Marray]] (men's doubles), [[Andy Murray]] (men's singles), [[John Lloyd (tennis)|John Lloyd]], [[Jeremy Bates (tennis)|Jeremy Bates]], [[Jo Durie]], [[Jamie Murray]] and [[Heather Watson]] (mixed doubles) winning titles in the Open Era.
==Financial context== London's financial industry has [[economic boom|boomed]] since the [[deregulation]] of British financial markets (the "[[Big Bang (financial markets)|Big Bang]]") in the 1980s under the [[Margaret Thatcher|Thatcher government]] — but has also become dominated by foreign companies, especially American [[investment bank]]s, rather than British firms (a result opposite to the original intention of the reforms).
The analogy is typically used to mark a debate over whether it matters if an industry is primarily domestically owned if easing of foreign ownership restrictions allows the economy to benefit from foreign investment and increased global competition. The phrase can be used positively to assert the economic success of [[economic liberalism|liberal]] attitudes towards foreign ownership (and sometimes to emphasize that such attitudes promote a level playing field for domestic and foreign interests alike); or it can be used negatively to emphasize how these policies have eroded a nation's ability to produce globally leading domestic companies. This opposing perspective is represented by [[economic nationalism|economic patriotism and "national champion" policies]]. [[File:Asashoryu and Hakuho glare at each other 2008 May.jpg|thumb|left|190px|The 68th [[yokozuna]] [[Asashōryū Akinori|Asasyoryu]] and the 69th yokozuna [[Hakuho]], who are both from Mongolia]] The analogy has also been used in policy discourses outside Britain – most notably in the business discourse of Japan,<ref>Sprague, Jonathan : [https://web.archive.org/web/20051204190211/http://pathfinder.com/asiaweek/magazine/2000/0922/biz.takeovers.html "Foreigners at the Wheel : A new boss at scandal-hit Mitsubishi Motors"], 22 September 2000, ''[[Asiaweek|Asiaweek.com]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.analyticajapan.com/glossmain.html#w "DATABASE: GLOSSARY OF JAPANESE TERMS"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006092339/http://www.analyticajapan.com/glossmain.html#w#w |date=6 October 2010 }}, ''ANALYTICA JAPAN: FINANCIAL RESEARCH''</ref> whose financial markets and other parts of the economy (as of 2006) have not yet been substantially opened up to foreign competition compared with its international peers. It has also, for instance, been used in banking reform debates in [[Republic of Korea|South Korea]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://times.hankooki.com/lpage/biz/200611/kt2006112119004911880.htm |title=::: The Korea Times ::: |publisher=Times.hankooki.com |date= |accessdate=2013-07-06}}</ref> as well as in discussing [[business process outsourcing]] in India.<ref>http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu/createpdf.cfm?articleid=875{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==Sports in Japan== The term has also frequently been appearing in sports in Japan since late 20th century, including [[sumo]] where [[Kisenosato Yutaka|there has been only one Japanese-born yokozuna since 1998]] as most of the top players have been from Mongolia or [[Polynesia]]. Similarly in [[combat sports]] (''kakutougi''), [[K-1]] was the biggest [[kickboxing]] promotion of the world, whereas [[Pride Fighting Championships]] was the biggest [[mixed martial arts]] promotion of the world. Nevertheless, both K-1 and Pride had few Japanese-born popular players or champions. The vast majority of prominent competitors in K-1 came from the Netherlands or Thailand, while Pride's biggest names were from Brazil, United States, and Russia.{{cn|date=August 2018}}
